segments.text: September 12, sitting in almost central Oklahoma City in the living room with Elaine Bezell Thompson, going to record her recollections of the teens and part of the 20s at Texas A&M.
Now, Mrs. Thompson, would you respond just briefly so we'll be sure your mic is working?
Well, I'll try.
That's enough.
We've unearthed a few.
Oh, look at that.
Mrs. Thompson, would you describe the background of your parents?
Introduce us to your parents.
Where did they grow up?
When did they get to Texas?
Well, they were... See, I'm already not sure about... My father...
I know he lived, he was born in Washington County, I think.
And his father died when I was under four years old.
And my grandmother came and lived with us all the rest of her life.
She lived to be 91.
And so I don't know much about the background of his...
Were they farmers?
They were farmers.
And she was very ambitious for him.
She was determined that he was going to have a fine education.
And so they had good years and bad years.
That's the way that Brazos bought them farming country-wise.
It was either wonderful or bad.
And so they had good years.
Where did your mother grow up?
My mother was born in Tennessee, and I don't know anything about that far background.
Where did your parents meet?
Navasota.
After his first...
was superintendent of schools in Navasota.
And then when I was four, we moved away and went to Denton.
Denton, Texas.
Did your dad grow up in a church-going family?
Yes.
Do I dare ask which?
Well, his family were Baptists, and he married my mother, who was a Methodist.
And all through the years, they stayed with their same denomination.
Why they didn't combine, which would have been a lot better, you know, because...
But after we got to A&M, you know, so different there.
Now, I don't know whether to go ahead with that part about the... Sure, sure.
Guy and Hall, I'm sure you're probably familiar with Guy and Hall was built...
while we were down there.
And the way things were, every Sunday morning, the whole cadet corps, with all the full uniforms and everything, marched into Guyon Hall for the church service.
And my father didn't like that at all.
He said there was every denomination, every race,

in the borough in that full auditorium for all those boys to march in there and sit down and go to sleep the ones that were not interested and he didn't think that was good and so he came up with the idea that he was going to have a good speaker he knew so many ministers out over the

country that were fine well just good reputations and all and they'd have a different one every Sunday they had one of each you know one time it would be Methodist maybe the next time it would be a Jewish robbery it was a strange way of doing things but that
It was the only way he could see that they could get everybody some time.
Did he help select the individual speakers?
He did that.
He did that?
He did that.
And he knew so many of them because my brother and I went on summer vacations with him after
after my brother and I were born, we went every summer to someplace where he was getting another degree.
And every Sunday we went to a church because he knew all about the minister.
And, oh, he'd either read books about him.
He was well informed on.
So I don't know exactly.
I was not old enough to know how that turned out, but it was a very unusual way of doing that.
And as far as you remember, there were Protestant, Catholic, and Jewish speakers.
Well, just whoever was, well, yes, I think so, yeah.
As far as you recall, how was your father selected to be the president at the Agricultural and Mechanical College of Texas?
How was he selected?
I don't know how he was selected.
And you were four years old when they got there?
Is that right?
I was born in 1904, and I was four years old when we went to Denton.
I was living in Navasota, because I was born in Navasota, and my mother's family all in Navasota.
All right, so you were then 11 when you and your family moved to college.
Is that what it was called then?
Uh-huh.
Yeah.
All right.
Do you remember your first impressions of A&M?
Well, see, I got four years in Denton first.
So that's where I started the school, in Denton.
And I'm not just sure.
I had a feeling I was about fourth grade or fifth grade when I came, when we moved down there.
I'm not good on dates about when that was.
Did you enjoy getting to college, to A&M, as a little girl?
Well, it was, you know, it was different than when I was in high school, of course.

but but i had um the dean of agriculture lived right down the street from us and his their daughter was lily best kyle kyle field you know and so she was my best friend on the campus when we were children we played together
And she's about the only little girl that I remember playing with because she was so close.
What do you remember about the Kyle family?
We don't know much about Dean Kyle in terms of personality.
Well, I don't remember anything except mother and father.
Was he a nice, pleasant man?
Oh, yes.
Yes, the family was really very nice.
What did two little girls do to, what kind of fun and games did you all play?
We played dolls.
I can even remember, it didn't have to be a real doll.
We all had dolls.
We had plenty of toys, but we had lots of dolls.
But I can remember one time, she and I were,
After the woodpile was, of course, they all had wood fire places.
And we took just a log of wood and we put baby clothes on it.
And that was something I hadn't thought of in a long time, but I remember doing that.
Do you remember any mischief that you all ever got into?
I don't remember any.
I don't think we did.
So mother didn't have to spank or anything like that?
No, I'm sure maybe she did, but I don't remember.
Describe the president's house where you all lived.
Well, it was a real old-fashioned house, and I just loved it.
Well, I say I loved it, but it was just home to me.
I've lived in three presents homes from the time I left Navasota till I got married.
How lovely, what a nice picture of it.
Does that look like it?
Oh, it's exactly like it, sure.
Where was your room?
Well, it was one of these upstairs front ones.
I don't remember.
I can see my grandmother had one of them.
My mother and father had the first one.
My grandmother, and then I had my, thanks for having his.
So we pretty well filled up the house.
Did you all ever play any games out on those porches?
No, I don't think.
The downstairs porch, we probably did.
And I'll tell you, I don't know whether this is at least a bit interesting, but the thing I remember about the downstairs porch, they had greenery.
shrubs and things across the front that sort of hid the where the chairs were behind it and I had a parrot and the parrot was really a good talker and then I'd put the parrot up in the
just on one of the little branches and I'd sit back in the chair and then the cadets would walk by and this parrot would say, hello, like that.
And I would just be so embarrassed I could hardly stand.
Now that's the kind of things you remember when you're 95 years old.
And those are the good things that we want.
I can't see if that is anything that could possibly help you.
Do you remember where the parrot came from?
No.
How long did you have it?
I don't know but it was so funny when he sang grand opera and I did all kinds of things.
We had it for quite a long time.
Did he have a name?
What was his name?
Polly, what did you say?
Polly Parrott.
a black couple that worked for us.
See, I'm just going from one something to another.
Henrietta and Ulysses S. Grant McElroy.
So this parrot was just called Henrietta, Henrietta, Grant.
Where did they live?
Did they live there?
Had quarters out in the back.
In the back?
Were there other black families living anywhere nearby?
No, because, let's see, I have to clear myself now.
Yes, it would be there.
The reason I hate to switch off, if you can cut it off,
You know, around college.
And they, for your family, she was the maid and cook?
Yep.
And what did he do?
Well, he drove the car.
Okay.
My father, I will have to admit, they never did learn to be expert at driving cars.
The children will say...
Y'all moved there in 1915.
Did y'all, you went, I presume, went on the train?
Oh, sure.
Well, I guess, let's see.
From Denton to College Station?
Well, we had a car somewhere along in there, but I can't remember just when the
What kind of cars were they, do you remember?
I don't remember the name of it, but I remember certain things about the cars.
I remember my father had to open the front lights up and light them and close them back up again, some kind of gas lights or something.
And they were all, of course, open, and then they had canvas

little curtains that would come down to keep the rain out if you were lucky and of course the roads were nothing but slippery mud we used to drive down to navasota on weekends to visit the relatives and and it was as if it rained it was a pretty bad where when you got to to a m where did you go to school
Brian.
And how did you get to Brian?
On a streetcar, trolley.
All the campus children got on the trolley and we went to grade school, all up, graduated from high school that way.
So did you graduate from Brian High School?
What year?
Do you remember how many were in the senior class?
I've got my yearbook right there.
Ralph, would you want to get the yearbook?
Describe what you recall about Bryan High School.
Was it fun?
Did you enjoy it?
Yes.
I'm telling you, when you're at that age, high school age, and living in a situation like that,
You always kind of had your eyes on the freshman A&M students.
And it was kind of tough on the high school boys.
But we had a good football team.
And of course, some of us were not allowed to date the A&M boys anyway.
So until later.
Was that a rule for you?
Were you not allowed to date the A&M boys?
Well, not until I was a certain age.
And then I don't think I had any dates with anybody until I was 16, which seems about right to me, I guess, maybe.
But it was kind of a touchy thing with the high school boys.
I bet this is the annual.
Do you want to just see what it looks like?
Let's see.
I'm turning the pages now.
Looks like about 42 or 43 in your senior class.
Now when you finished high school, where did you want to go to college?
A&M.
Where did your family want you to go to college?
Well, they didn't want me to go to college at A&M.
My father had great expectations, but I was never the great student.
My brother was, but I had a lot of other interests.
You'd think I was a frivolous butterfly, if you hear me tell about my fun I had at Texas A&M.
But I just loved everything about Texas A&M.
How did you persuade your parents to allow you to attend A&M?
Well, they just gave in.
They didn't complain too much.
I never did want to ever go away from home.

so they they just let me do it of course my father had me taking every course in the world high school i took four years of latin and about four years of well all the math and english and ancient history and and then went to oh and physics
And then when I got to A&M, that first, I'd had two years at A&M.
And he had me take chemistry and analytics at A&M, because I had trigonometry before in high school.
So I really took all the, he had great,
education ambition, I guess, for me.
But I just didn't want to go off to school.
Did your father believe in equal education for women?
Did he think women should be educated as well as men?
Well, yes, I'm sure he did, but he didn't mean for them to be a Texas A&M man.
Of course, yeah.
I had heard that he certainly did.
Oh yes, he sure would.
When you enrolled as a freshman at A&M, do you know how many other coeds there were that year?
I think Helen Dowdy was one of them, and I think she
moved to go to live with her uncle and aunt who were on the campus, and I had an idea that she wanted to do the same thing.
I never did know for sure that that was right, but she lived with them for those two years.
Have there been any women enrolled before you and her?
Yes, and I don't know whether there was...
I have a yearbook over here, too, I thought you might be interested in seeing.
And it seemed like somewhere in one of those books that it said that there was some talk about women... Did...
When you took classes, you were in a room full of young men.
Where did a young lady sit?
Just right in there.
You might go in and sit down, and the boys might come in and sit all around the room.
But we just sat in there like the rest of them.
Thank you.
Were there any rules?
that your father gave you as an undergraduate about what you could and could not do while you were an Aggie?
No, they just treated me just like they did when I was in high school, I think.
Was it okay then for you to date A&M students?
Oh, yes, yes.
Tell me about some A&M social events.
Well, they had absolutely super-duper balls, two of them, Thanksgiving Hop and the Ross Vaughn Tear Hop.
And I mean, it was decorated to clear out the mess hall.
to take every bit of furniture out except for the line of chairs for all the big number of chaperones, the faculty people that they would invite to be chaperones.
And they always had a grand march.
Were the young men, did you always have a date?
Sure, oh yes.
Did you then have a dance card where you signed?
Yes, a dance card, you fill that out.
Where did they get their dates?
The, pardon me, the faculty.
people had kept the girls, and they could invite their girls from home, and the hostess would invite them to come, and the parents let them come down and stay with those people.
The faculty houses were just full, and in our house, we've had as many as six or eight stay at our house.
Did young ladies come down from CIA?
They just came down from all over the state.
And I presume more often than not came on the train?
Yes.
At those dances, was there any alcohol served?
Not supposed to be at all.
Of course, there was never any drink, and you'd get expelled if you got caught more than once or twice, I think.
I don't remember exactly about that.
But once in a while, there would be somebody at the dance that would tag you.
Of course, it was tagging.
Oh, just so much, because there were so many stags.
And if anybody would tag me that had had something to drink, one of my friends was just right there.
Describe what a young lady would have worn to one of those balls.
We had real fancy clothes and real high heels to dance in.
My children heard me say I didn't know that people weren't just supposed to have hurt feet, hurting feet.
Because I always had hurting feet from dancing.
Now those dances, and this will surprise you probably if you don't already know it.
The dance would last from 9 to 12.
Then you'd have an hour off.
And you'd go to these different places.
My mother always had a little midnight supper, light, something, you know.
And the boys and girls would take part in that.
And then when the hour was up, or exactly how long it was, we'd all go back to the mess hall and dance till about three.

and you know why my feet hurt but it was simply wonderful it was just the most fun of anything in this world and the ross volunteer hop was in the other part of the year and these were held in was sebisa hall built yet sebisa dining hall yes so they were held there
Well, there was a great big mess hall that all the student body ate in there.
Where did the orchestra come from?
Well, of course they had an orchestra right there, but I don't remember now whether they had outside orchestras come in or not.
These beautiful dresses, did you all buy them or did someone make them for you?
Well, mine were mostly bought.
We'd go to Houston to shop.
And that's where I got my high heel shoes.
And was a Houston trip an all day or an overnight trip?
I believe we'd spend the night in the hotels.
I've forgotten exactly how far it is to Houston.
Do you remember?
About 100 miles.
100 miles, yeah.
No, I think we went down there to shop.
Bryan was not a very good place to shop, as you can imagine.
And did your parents have you take piano, ballet?
I took piano lessons from the time I was a little girl until I...
but got to Norman and even took piano lessons at OU.
When you were at A&M, who was your teacher?
Miss Friley.
Friley.
Is that name familiar to you?
No, ma'am, it's not.
Mr. Friley, or Dr. Friley, I've forgotten which we called him, he went from A&M to become president of another school.
And I used to know the Frileys and my family, but I can't remember which school it was.
What did he teach?
Do you remember?
I don't remember that either.
I don't remember anything except the music teacher.
So she had a number of piano students?
Did you take ballet or any other?
I took the Scottish fling.
I don't know why, and that lasted about a year, but
And I wasn't carried away with that.
But of course, you know, the Ross Volunteers, I just thought that was the most wonderful group.
And I guess they still have that fancy drill they do.
And people would come from everywhere.
cars, it was all cars at that time, a lot of people had cars.
And they would come, you'd have cars all around the field and they'd get out and they were just wonderful.
Did the Ross Volunteers wear those spotless white uniforms?
Oh, you bet.
Yes, they had the swords and everything.
I just loved all that military.
When a group of young people wanted to go out on a picnic, wanted to go somewhere off campus, where were the favorite places?
The Brazos River.
And they'd even swim in it, and I wouldn't get in that water.
But I can remember we'd have, oh, there'd be some kind of a truck.
We'd get in a truck and one of the boys would have a guitar.
And we'd go down there and have picnics and swim if he wanted to.
What kind of a bathing suit did the young lady wear then?
It was not like you have now.
They were just one piece, but a cover-up.
Bare legs?
You didn't have the long skirt.
Was that your mother's?
Oh, well, no.
Part of the time, I think we got to where we had bare legs, but I think my mother sewed long black stockings onto them,
bathing suit.
Now, did a typical young lady in that era ever smoke?
You know, I don't even remember about that.
I think you would have if you had.
Yeah, I think so.
But it would be the rare thing if they did.
Now, this is prohibition time.
Where did the, if there was any alcohol, where did they get it?
I have no idea.
